IT TAKES only one great artist to keep a tradition alive. And through much of its history, the tradition of constructed sculpture has lived almost that precariously. Invented by Picasso, whose constructions offered the first alternatives to certain fundamental assumptions about sculptural aesthetics and methods since ancient times, it was virtually reinvented by David Smith. Since the latter's death, its destiny has been very much m the hands of Anthony Caro
